I’m so excited and honored to announce my third solo exhibition and first solo show in San Francisco! “Black Chrysalis” opens July 7 with the amazing @schlomer_haus_gallery 💕 hope to see you there! 

**SAVE THE DATE**

Schlomer Haus Gallery is thrilled to debut Rakeem Cunningham’s new solo show “Black Chrysalis” opening Friday, July 7th.

Using photography, collage, installation, and video to explore the nuances of queer black experience, Cunningham photographs himself playing and posing in the studio, informed and surrounded by a multiverse of niche subcultures. Each portrait is a declaration of subjectivity and existence—proof of self-validation and an ongoing healing journey. 

"Black Chrysalis" opens Friday, July 7th 5-9pm and the artist will be in attendance. Mark your calendars as you will not want to miss it.

So happy to a part of Destination Crenshaw. A big big thank you to @lookatdominique for always looking out and supporting black artists. Destination Crenshaw invites you to attend a private art exhibition, Moments & Memories, on Friday, July 14th from 6-9PM hosted at the LA Council District 8 Crenshaw office. This exhibit was curated to showcase nine incredibly talented Black LA-based artists working in mediums ranging from film photography, digital photography, figurative painting, abstract painting, and mixed media. We will be opening the event with remarks around 6:30PM surrounding Destination Crenshaw's recent and upcoming projects as well as to highlight the artists being featured.

@rakeemc is a Black queer icon. 

Born in Pacoima and currently based in LA, @UCLA graduate Rakeem Cunningham is a one-of-a-kind multimedia artist. He uses photography, collage, installation, and video to explore the nuances of the queer Black experience while forming clear declarations around subjectivity and validation. 

His unique and powerful works draw inspiration from manga, anime, and video games. Photoshoots featuring his work are often orchestrated to include himself and others in cosplay and other transformative, liberating, and restorative gestures. 

Visit Rakeem's profile to see more of his exciting work @rakeemc

We recently asked several readers and community members, “Who is Carla?” Carla is CONNECTIVE, according to Rakeem Cunningham, artist, art worker, and lover of Carla.⁠
⁠
“Connectivity is probably the most important thing in the art world because otherwise we’re living in these bubbles and we’re not really examining or growing. I don’t think you can be an artist, arts publication, or gallery on your own. Trying to create connectivity within a city that is fragmented is such a beautiful goal for Carla to have.”
